fact that in Cato's time, when plays were given, no regular pro- vision was made for seating the audience. The early custom had been to stand. In the theatre as Cicero knew it—both the tem- porary wooden structures and the one permanent theatre of Pompey —prima cavea meant the lowest tiers of scats in the long semi- circular rows rising one above the other to the top of the theatre (ullzbna, or summa cavea).
